Use reqwest to hit DuckDuckGo Lite's HTML endpoint and extract results with simple string scanning. No need for `scraper` or `select.rs`:

```rust
async fn search_web(
    client: &reqwest::Client,
    query: &str,
    max_results: usize,
) -> Result<Vec<String>> {
    let encoded_query = url_encode(query);
    let url = format!("https://lite.duckduckgo.com/lite/?q={encoded_query}");

    let resp = client
        .get(&url)
        .header("User-Agent", "forge-research/0.1")
        .send()
        .await?;

    if !resp.status().is_success() {
        return Ok(vec![format!("HTTP {}", resp.status())]);
    }

    let body = resp.text().await?;
    Ok(extract_ddg_results(&body, max_results))
}
```

The HTML parser is just a state machine that finds `href=` patterns and strips tags from nearby text:

```rust
fn extract_ddg_results(html: &str, max: usize) -> Vec<String> {
    let mut results = Vec::new();
    let mut pos = 0;
    while results.len() < max {
        let link_start = match html[pos..].find("href=\"") {
            Some(i) => pos + i + 6,
            None => break,
        };
        let link_end = match html[link_start..].find('"') {
            Some(i) => link_start + i,
            None => break,
        };
        let link = &html[link_start..link_end];
        if link.starts_with("http") && !link.contains("duckduckgo.com") {
            let snippet = strip_tags(&html[link_end..(link_end + 300).min(html.len())]);
            results.push(format!("{link}\n  {}", snippet.trim()));
        }
        pos = link_end + 1;
    }
    results
}

fn strip_tags(html: &str) -> String {
    let mut result = String::new();
    let mut in_tag = false;
    for c in html.chars() {
        if c == '<' { in_tag = true; }
        else if c == '>' { in_tag = false; }
        else if !in_tag { result.push(c); }
    }
    result.split_whitespace().collect::<Vec<_>>().join(" ")
}
```

Write a minimal percent-encoder inline. For search queries you only need to handle ASCII:

```rust
fn url_encode(input: &str) -> String {
    let mut result = String::new();
    for byte in input.bytes() {
        match byte {
            b'A'..=b'Z' | b'a'..=b'z' | b'0'..=b'9' | b'-' | b'_' | b'.' | b'~' => {
                result.push(byte as char);
            }
            b' ' => result.push('+'),
            _ => result.push_str(&format!("%{byte:02X}")),
        }
    }
    result
}
```

This follows RFC 3986 unreserved characters. Spaces become `+` (application/x-www-form-urlencoded style), everything else gets percent-encoded. For a search tool this covers all realistic inputs without pulling in the `url` or `percent-encoding` crate.

