Three-tier detection: arch check, known paths, then Python module:

```rust
fn probe_mlx() -> (bool, Option<String>) {
    // First check: is this Apple Silicon?
    if !super::mlx::is_available() {
        return (false, Some("Requires Apple Silicon Mac".to_string()));
    }

    // Second: check known Homebrew path
    let brew_path = std::path::Path::new("/opt/homebrew/bin/mlx_lm.server");
    if brew_path.exists() {
        return (true, None);
    }

    // Third: check PATH
    if let Ok(output) = std::process::Command::new("which")
        .arg("mlx_lm.server")
        .output()
    {
        if output.status.success() {
            return (true, None);
        }
    }

    // Fourth: check Python module directly
    if let Ok(output) = std::process::Command::new("python3")
        .args(["-c", "import mlx_lm"])
        .output()
    {
        if output.status.success() {
            return (true, Some("via python3 -m mlx_lm.server".to_string()));
        }
    }

    (false, Some("mlx_lm not installed".to_string()))
}
```

The reason field tells users exactly why detection failed or how it'll be invoked. For llama.cpp, do the same pattern but check multiple binary names (`llama-server`, platform-specific paths, `where`/`which` depending on OS). The probe runs once at startup and the result is cached for the session lifetime -- no need to re-probe.

